263—4. The name Epidamnus would most frequently be heard by a Roman in the accusative (e. g. in answer to the question quo is .?). To Roman ears Epidamnum (ἐπὶ damnum) sounded unlucky; hence the joke here, and the actual change of the name to Dyrrhachium when the town became a Roman colony (cf. 32 note). A similar case was that of the Greek colony Μαλόεις, the name of which the Romans first corrupted (from the acc. Μηλόεντα) into Maleuentum, and then changed to Beneuentum.
